'''Green hunting''' or '''eco-hunting''' is the practice of hunting [[game animals]] with tranquiliser dart guns<ref>http://www.ecologyandsociety.org/vol15/iss2/art28/ES-2009-3349.pdf</ref><ref name="artedocu">{{cite web|url=http://www.arte.tv/guide/fr/042013-000-A/la-biodiversite-menacee-quelles-solutions-pour-demain|title=La Biodiversité menacée : quelles solutions pour demain ?|date=11 April 2016|work=Programmes ARTE}}</ref> and the subsequent release of the live animals. Green hunting would typically be performed when tranquilisation of the animal is necessary for veterinary or monitoring purposes,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.krugerpark.co.za/krugerpark-times-2-8-green-alternative-hunting-19538.html|title=Kruger Park Times - The green alternative to hunting - Online News Publication...|publisher=}}</ref> or when animals are to be translocated.<ref name="artedocu" /> Green hunting has been advocated as a conservation-minded alternative to destructive hunting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2003/06/0616_030616_greenhunting.html|title=In Africa, Hunters Pay to Tranquilize Game for Research|publisher=National Geographic}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://video.nationalgeographic.com/video/rhino_white_greenhunt|title=Rhino Green Hunt|publisher=National Geographic}}</ref> However, criticism has sprung up over the possibility that in the interest of generating revenue, particular animals may undergo tranquilisation too frequently, with a case alleged where tranquilisation occurred once every two weeks,<ref name="nspca">{{cite web|url=http://www.nspca.co.za/page/green-hunting|title=Green Hunting|publisher=}}</ref> and the suggestion that this may be traumatising to the animals,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://speakupforthevoiceless.org/2014/06/26/green-hunting-good-or-bad/|title=Green Hunting – Good or Bad?|work=Speak Up For The Voiceless - International Animal Rescue Foundation - Environmental News and Media}}</ref> with consequences poorly studied.<ref name="nspca" />

