'''Potassium niobate''' (KNbO<sub>3</sub>) is a [[perovskite]] [[ferroelectric]] crystal. It has nonlinear optical coefficient properties, making it common in the manufacture of lasers.<ref name="Palik1998">{{cite book|last=Palik|first=Edward D.|title=Handbook of Optical Constants of Solids 3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VpuVttd2cuEC&pg=PA821|accessdate=13 December 2012|year=1998|publisher=Academic Press|isbn=978-0-12-544423-1|page=821}}</ref> Nanowires of potassium niobate have been used to produce tunable coherent light. The {{LD50}} for potassium niobate is 3000&nbsp;mg/kg (oral, rat).
==Crystal Structure== On cooling from high temperature, KNbO<sub>3</sub> undergoes a series of structural phase transitions. At 435&nbsp;°C, the crystal symmetry changes from cubic centrosymmetric (Pm3 ̅m) to [[tetragonal]] non-centrosymmetric (P4mm). On further cooling, at 225&nbsp;°C the crystal symmetry changes from tetragonal (P4mm) to [[orthorhombic]] (Amm2) and at −50&nbsp;°C from [[orthorhombic]] (Amm2) to [[rhombohedral]] (R3m).
==Use in research== Potassium niobate has been found useful in many different areas of [[materials science]] research,<ref name=ISF>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.2307/3931381 | volume = 62 | issue = 17 | pages = 264–265 | title = In Science Fields | journal = The Science News-Letter | date = 1952-10-25 | jstor = 3931381 }}{{Subscription required |via=[[JSTOR]]}}</ref> including properties of [[lasers]],<ref name=Science>{{Cite journal | volume = 267 | issue = 5206 | pages = 1920 | last = Regalado | first = Antonio | title = Blue-Light Special | journal = Science | series = New Series | date = 1995-03-31 | jstor = 2886437 | doi=10.1126/science.267.5206.1920 | bibcode = 1995Sci...267.1920R }}{{Subscription required |via=[[JSTOR]]}}</ref> [[quantum teleportation]],<ref name=Furusawa1998>{{Cite journal | volume = 282 | issue = 5389 | pages = 706–709 | last = Furusawa | first = A. |author2=J. L. Sørensen |author3=S. L. Braunstein |author4=C. A. Fuchs |author5=H. J. Kimble |author6=E. S. Polzik | title = Unconditional Quantum Teleportation | journal = Science | series = New Series | date = 1998-10-23 | jstor = 2899257 | doi=10.1126/science.282.5389.706 |bibcode=1998Sci...282..706F}}{{Subscription required |via=[[JSTOR]]}}</ref> and it has been used to study the optical properties of particulate [[composite materials]].<ref name=Lakhtakia2007>{{Cite journal | volume = 463 | issue = 2078 | pages = 583–592 | last = Lakhtakia | first = Akhlesh |author2=Tom G. Mackay | title = Electrical Control of the Linear Optical Properties of Particulate Composite Materials | journal = Proceedings of the Royal Society A | date = 2007-02-08 | jstor = 20209136 | doi=10.1098/rspa.2006.1783 | arxiv = physics/0607274 | bibcode = 2007RSPSA.463..583L }}{{Subscription required |via=[[JSTOR]]}}</ref>
In addition to research in electronic memory storage,<ref name=ISF /> potassium niobate is used in [[frequency doubling|resonant doubling]], a technique developed at the [[IBM Almaden Research Center]].<ref name=Science /> This technique allows small infrared lasers to convert output into blue light, a critical technology for the production of blue lasers and technology dependent upon them.
